                     <head>Pine tree</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="Pine_cone.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="thumb/Pine_cone.jpg"/>
                     <head>Pine cone</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="View_over_Segya_from_top.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="thumb/View_over_Segya_from_top.jpg"/>
                     <head>View over Segya from top</head>
                  </figure>
               </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve"> The place is characterized by a hilly landscape with pine trees and quiet surroundings. However, Sakiet Sidi Youssef witnessed commotions in previous times. Located on the Algerian-Tunisian communication road, only a few kilometers from the border, the town in February 1958 sadly gained international attention. During the Algerian Revolution, the inhabitants of Sakiet Sidi Youssef had been supporting refugees fleeing from the adjoining Algerian village Souk Ahras. Subsequently, the French occupation forces retaliated against this assistance and bombarded the Tunisian town. This reprisal attack led to more than 60 dead and even more injured.</p>
